        id: "coyote-tobacco",
        title: "Coyote Tobacco (Utah, USA)",
        year: -10000,
        yearLabel: "c. 10,000 BC (12,300 years ago)",
        description:
          "In a remarkable discovery that pushes back the timeline of tobacco use in North America by thousands of years, archaeologists studying an ancient hearth site in the Great Salt Lake Desert of Utah found seeds from the hallucinogenic species known as Coyote Tobacco (Nicotiana attenuata) that were radiocarbon-dated to approximately 12,300 years ago — placing their use firmly in the late Pleistocene, during the Ice Age, and making them the oldest confirmed evidence of human tobacco use in the world.\n\nThe discovery, published in the journal Nature Human Behaviour in 2021, was made at the Wishbone site, a hunter-gatherer camp in the northern Great Salt Lake Desert. The site dates to the early occupation of the Great Basin by Paleoindian peoples who lived in a landscape very different from today's barren salt flats — during the late Pleistocene, the area was the shore of a large freshwater lake surrounded by marshes and grasslands that supported a diverse community of plants and animals.\n\nCoyote Tobacco is a wild species of Nicotiana native to western North America. Unlike cultivated tobacco (Nicotiana tabacum), which was domesticated in South America and spread northward, Coyote Tobacco has never been domesticated — it grows wild in disturbed soils and open areas across the American West. The plant contains nicotine and other psychoactive alkaloids that produce stimulant, analgesic (pain-relieving), and mildly hallucinogenic effects when consumed. Indigenous peoples of the Great Basin and surrounding regions used Coyote Tobacco in ceremonial contexts for thousands of years, chewing the leaves, smoking them in pipes, or mixing them with other substances.\n\nThe significance of the Wishbone site discovery extends beyond the mere age of the tobacco seeds. The seeds were found in the remains of a hearth — a deliberately constructed fire pit — along with the bones of ducks and other waterbirds, indicating that the people who used this site were engaged in organized hunting and food processing. The presence of tobacco seeds in this context suggests that tobacco use was already integrated into the daily life or ceremonial practices of these early Americans.\n\nPreviously, the oldest evidence of tobacco use in North America dated to approximately 3,000 years ago (1,000 BC), based on nicotine residue found in smoking pipes. The Wishbone site pushes this date back by approximately 9,000 years, demonstrating that the human relationship with tobacco — one of the most culturally significant plants in Native American history — extends deep into the Pleistocene.\n\nThe discovery also connects to broader questions about the role of psychoactive substances in early human cultures. The use of Coyote Tobacco at 12,300 years ago is contemporary with the earliest rock art at sites like Serrania de la Lindosa in Colombia and the proposed onset of ayahuasca use in the Amazon. Together, these findings suggest that the human engagement with mind-altering plants is not a recent development but a fundamental aspect of our species' relationship with the natural world — one that extends back to the very earliest periods of human presence in the Americas.",
