        id: "karahan-tepe",
        title: "Karahan Tepe (Turkey)",
        year: -9750,
        yearLabel: "c. 9,750 BC",
        description:
          "Karahan Tepe is an extraordinary Neolithic site in southeastern Turkey's Şanlıurfa Province that has emerged as one of the most significant archaeological discoveries of the twenty-first century. Dating to approximately 9,750 BC, the site is contemporaneous with — and in some respects may predate — its more famous neighbor Göbekli Tepe, located approximately 35 kilometers to the northwest. Together, these sites are forcing a fundamental reassessment of the capabilities, social organization, and spiritual lives of pre-agricultural hunter-gatherer societies.\n\nThe site was first surveyed in 1997 but systematic excavations did not begin until 2019, led by Necmi Karul of Istanbul University under the auspices of Turkey's Ministry of Culture and Tourism. The excavations have revealed a complex of structures carved into and built upon the natural bedrock, including T-shaped pillars similar to those at Göbekli Tepe, elaborately carved animal reliefs, and a remarkable subterranean chamber featuring a row of carved stone phalluses emerging from the bedrock floor — unique in Neolithic archaeology.\n\nThe most striking feature discovered so far is the so-called 'Pillar Building' — a semi-subterranean structure containing multiple T-shaped limestone pillars arranged in a roughly circular pattern around a central pillar. The pillars are carved with reliefs of animals including snakes, foxes, and leopards, as well as abstract symbols whose meaning remains unknown. Some pillars appear to represent stylized human figures, with carved arms, hands, and clothing details — similar to the anthropomorphic pillars at Göbekli Tepe.\n\nKarahan Tepe's significance lies in what it tells us about the society that built it. The conventional narrative of human cultural development holds that monumental architecture — structures requiring the organized labor of large groups over extended periods — only became possible after the development of agriculture, which provided the food surplus necessary to support specialized builders, artists, and religious leaders. Karahan Tepe, like Göbekli Tepe, shatters this narrative: the site was built by hunter-gatherers who had not yet domesticated plants or animals, suggesting that the impulse to create monumental sacred spaces may have preceded — and possibly even driven — the transition to agriculture.\n\nThe discovery of Karahan Tepe also confirms that Göbekli Tepe was not an isolated anomaly but part of a broader phenomenon. Since excavations began at these two sites, numerous additional sites with similar T-shaped pillars and carved reliefs have been identified across southeastern Turkey, including Sayburç, Harbetsuvan Tepesi, and Sefer Tepe. This 'Taş Tepeler' (Stone Hills) network suggests the existence of a sophisticated, interconnected cultural tradition across a wide region of the northern Fertile Crescent during the early Neolithic — millennia before the emergence of the Sumerian civilization that was previously considered the world's first complex society.\n\nThe ongoing excavations at Karahan Tepe promise to yield further revelations. Only a small fraction of the site has been excavated, and ground-penetrating radar surveys indicate extensive buried structures awaiting discovery. Each new excavation season has produced surprises, and archaeologists acknowledge that our understanding of the site — and of the Neolithic revolution itself — is likely to change significantly as more evidence comes to light.",
