        id: "urfa-man",
        title: "Urfa Man (Şanlıurfa, Turkey)",
        year: -9000,
        yearLabel: "c. 9,000 BC",
        description:
          "Urfa Man is a remarkable life-sized limestone statue discovered in 1993 during construction work in the Yeni Mahalle neighborhood of Şanlıurfa, Turkey. Dating to approximately 9,000 BC — roughly contemporary with the later phases of Göbekli Tepe — it is one of the oldest known naturalistic human sculptures in the world and provides a tantalizing glimpse into the spiritual and artistic world of Neolithic Anatolia.\n\nThe statue stands approximately 1.8 meters (6 feet) tall and is carved from a single block of limestone. The figure is depicted standing upright with its hands clasped in front of its body, covering or holding its genitals — a pose that has been interpreted as either ritualistic modesty, a gesture of fertility symbolism, or a sign of reverence. The face is striking: it has deeply carved obsidian eyes set into the stone (the earliest known use of obsidian for sculptural inlay), a prominent nose, and no mouth — a deliberate omission that gives the figure an enigmatic, almost otherworldly expression.\n\nThe statue's obsidian eyes are particularly significant. Obsidian — volcanic glass — was one of the most valued materials of the Neolithic world, prized for its ability to be worked into razor-sharp cutting tools and for its lustrous, mirror-like surface. The nearest obsidian sources to Şanlıurfa are in central Anatolia and around Lake Van, hundreds of kilometers to the north and east, indicating long-distance trade networks or travel by the communities of southeastern Turkey during this period.\n\nUrfa Man is now displayed in the Şanlıurfa Archaeological Museum, where it occupies a place of honor among the growing collection of Neolithic artifacts from the region. The statue is often interpreted in connection with the T-shaped pillars at Göbekli Tepe and Karahan Tepe, which also appear to represent stylized human figures (with carved arms and hands) but in a more abstract, pillar-like form. Urfa Man may represent the same type of being depicted in the pillar sculptures — perhaps an ancestor, a spirit, a deity, or a specific individual of importance within the community.\n\nThe discovery of Urfa Man, together with the other extraordinary Neolithic finds from southeastern Turkey, has fundamentally changed our understanding of the artistic and spiritual capabilities of early Neolithic peoples. The sophistication of the carving, the deliberate use of exotic materials (obsidian), and the scale of the sculpture all demonstrate that the societies of this region possessed not only the technical skills for monumental construction (as shown at Göbekli Tepe) but also a rich tradition of representational art that expressed complex ideas about the human form, identity, and the relationship between the living and the spiritual world.",
