        id: "paracas-candelabra",
        title: "The Paracas Candelabra (Pisco Bay, Peru)",
        year: -200,
        yearLabel: "c. 200 BC",
        description:
          "The Paracas Candelabra (also known as the Candelabro de Paracas) is a massive geoglyph carved into the sandy, north-facing hillside of the Paracas Peninsula on Pisco Bay, along the Pacific coast of Peru. Measuring approximately 180 meters (590 feet) tall and 70 meters (230 feet) wide, with trenches approximately 60 centimeters deep cut into the hardpan, the figure is visible from as far as 20 kilometers out to sea — a beacon-like presence on the barren coastal hillside that has been puzzling observers since it was first documented by European explorers.\n\nThe geoglyph's shape is variously described as a candelabrum (candelabra), a trident, a cactus, or a stylized tree. The central shaft rises vertically with three sets of branches extending symmetrically on either side, creating a broadly symmetrical figure with a distinctive tripartite form. The identity and purpose of the figure have been the subject of extensive debate among archaeologists, historians, and alternative researchers.\n\nThe most commonly accepted dating places the Candelabra's creation at approximately 200 BC, associating it with the Paracas culture — a sophisticated pre-Columbian society that flourished along the southern coast of Peru from approximately 800 BC to 100 BC. The Paracas culture is best known for its extraordinary textiles (among the finest ever produced in the pre-Columbian Americas), its practice of skull trepanation (surgical opening of the skull), and the enigmatic elongated skulls found in many Paracas burials — the result of deliberate cranial modification through binding during infancy.\n\nSeveral theories have been proposed for the Candelabra's purpose. Some researchers interpret it as a navigational landmark for ancient seafarers — the figure's orientation and visibility from the sea would make it an effective waypoint for vessels traveling along the Peruvian coast. Others connect it to the Paracas culture's religious practices, interpreting it as a representation of the Viracocha (the Andean creator deity), a lightning rod (trident), or a hallucinogenic cactus (the San Pedro cactus, Echinopsis pachanoi, which has been used in Andean shamanic rituals for at least 3,000 years and has a vaguely similar branching form).\n\nThe Candelabra's preservation in such an arid, windswept environment is remarkable. The coastal desert of Peru is one of the driest places on Earth, receiving virtually no rainfall, and the figure has survived for over two millennia with minimal erosion. However, the soft sandy material from which it is carved is vulnerable to human disturbance, and the site has been damaged by foot traffic and unauthorized vehicle access. Conservation efforts have been complicated by the remoteness of the site and limited resources for monitoring and protection.\n\nThe Paracas Candelabra is often discussed in connection with the Nazca Lines, the famous geoglyphs located approximately 200 kilometers to the south, which are attributed to the Nazca culture (c. 200 BC–700 AD) and include enormous depictions of animals, plants, and geometric figures that are only fully visible from the air. While the two sets of geoglyphs are separated by both distance and cultural attribution, they share the common mystery of why ancient Peruvian cultures invested enormous effort in creating images that could only be fully appreciated from perspectives that they themselves could not easily achieve.",
