        description:
          "Palenque is one of the most exquisite and architecturally refined cities of the ancient Maya civilization, located in the lowland jungle of the Mexican state of Chiapas at the foot of a chain of low hills covered by dense tropical forest. The city's remarkably well-preserved temples, palaces, and carved stone panels make it one of the most studied and most visited archaeological sites in Mesoamerica, and its royal dynasty — particularly the famous King K'inich Janaab Pakal (Pakal the Great) — is among the best documented in the Maya world.\n\nPalenque's history spans approximately a thousand years, from its founding around 200 BC to its final abandonment in the early 10th century AD. The city reached its peak during the reign of Pakal the Great (615–683 AD), who ascended to the throne at the age of 12 and ruled for 68 years — one of the longest reigns in Maya history. Under Pakal and his sons Chan Bahlum II and Kan Balam II, Palenque was transformed from a regional center into one of the most powerful and artistically accomplished cities in the Maya world.\n\nThe architecture of Palenque is distinguished by its elegance and its integration with the natural landscape. The Palace — a complex of interconnected buildings and courtyards built over centuries — features a unique four-story tower that may have served as an astronomical observatory or a watchtower. The Temple of the Inscriptions — Palenque's most famous structure — is a stepped pyramid containing one of the most elaborate royal tombs ever discovered in the Americas.\n\nThe tomb of Pakal the Great, discovered by Mexican archaeologist Alberto Ruz Lhuillier in 1952 after four years of excavation, is located deep within the Temple of the Inscriptions, accessed by a narrow internal stairway that descends approximately 25 meters from the temple's summit to a vaulted burial chamber at ground level. The sarcophagus is covered by an intricately carved limestone lid depicting Pakal at the moment of his death, descending into the jaws of the earth (Xibalba, the Maya underworld). The lid's imagery — which shows Pakal falling along a cruciform World Tree flanked by celestial serpents — has been interpreted by some alternative researchers (most famously Erich von Däniken) as depicting an astronaut operating a spacecraft, though this interpretation is rejected by Maya scholars who read the imagery as a standard Maya representation of death, rebirth, and cosmic order.\n\nPalenque's sculptural tradition is among the finest in the Maya world. The stucco portraits found in the Palace and temples are remarkable for their naturalistic rendering of human features — expressing individuality and emotion in a way that is rare in ancient Mesoamerican art. The hieroglyphic inscriptions at Palenque are among the most extensive and important in the Maya world, providing detailed records of royal genealogies, political alliances, military campaigns, and ritual activities.\n\nPalenque was designated a UNESCO World Heritage Site in 1987. The site remains only partially excavated — it is estimated that less than 10% of the ancient city has been explored, with hundreds of structures still hidden beneath the jungle canopy. Each new excavation season continues to yield discoveries that deepen our understanding of Maya civilization and the extraordinary people who built one of the most beautiful cities of the ancient world.",
