        id: "chichen-itza",
        title: "Chichen Itza — Serpent of Light (Mexico)",
        year: 550,
        yearLabel: "6th century AD",
        description:
          "Chichen Itza, located in the northern lowlands of Mexico's Yucatán Peninsula, is one of the most recognizable and most visited archaeological sites in the world — and home to one of the most spectacular demonstrations of ancient astronomical and architectural precision ever created. The site's centerpiece, El Castillo (the Temple of Kukulkan), was designed so that twice a year — during the spring and autumn equinoxes — the descending sun creates a shadow pattern on the pyramid's northern stairway that takes the form of a serpent slithering down from the temple to the earth.\n\nChichen Itza's origins date to the 6th century AD, when a Maya settlement was established near a large natural sinkhole (cenote) that provided a reliable water source in the otherwise dry karst landscape of the Yucatán. The site grew into one of the largest and most diverse cities in the Maya world, featuring architectural styles and artistic influences from multiple Mesoamerican traditions — suggesting that it served as a cosmopolitan center where different cultural groups interacted, traded, and exchanged ideas.\n\nEl Castillo is a step pyramid standing approximately 30 meters tall, with 91 steps on each of its four sides — totaling 364 steps, which, together with the temple platform at the top, equal 365: the number of days in the solar year. This numerical encoding of the calendar in the pyramid's architecture demonstrates the Maya obsession with time-keeping and their sophisticated understanding of the solar cycle.\n\nThe equinox phenomenon at El Castillo is the result of extraordinarily precise architectural planning. The pyramid is oriented so that its northwest corner faces the point on the horizon where the sun sets on the equinoxes. As the sun descends on the afternoon of the equinox, the stepped corners of the pyramid cast a series of triangular shadows onto the western balustrade of the northern stairway. These shadows create the appearance of a serpent's body — seven undulating triangles of light and shadow — that connect with a carved stone serpent head at the base of the stairway. The effect is a visual illusion of a serpent descending from the temple to the earth — interpreted as the descent of the feathered serpent deity Kukulkan (the Maya equivalent of the Aztec Quetzalcoatl) from the heavens.\n\nThis phenomenon, which occurs over a period of approximately 45 minutes on or near the equinox dates (March 20-21 and September 22-23), draws tens of thousands of visitors to Chichen Itza each year. The precision required to create this effect — accounting for the exact latitude, the sun's angle, the pyramid's dimensions, and the spacing of the stepped corners — demonstrates that the builders possessed detailed mathematical and astronomical knowledge and the engineering skill to translate that knowledge into architectural form.\n\nChichen Itza contains numerous other significant structures, including the Great Ball Court (the largest in Mesoamerica, measuring 168 by 70 meters), the Temple of Warriors (with its famous Chac Mool sculpture), the Cenote Sagrado (Sacred Cenote, into which offerings — including human sacrifices — were cast), and the Caracol (a cylindrical tower that served as an astronomical observatory, with windows aligned to Venus's extreme positions).\n\nChichen Itza was designated a UNESCO World Heritage Site in 1988 and was selected as one of the New Seven Wonders of the World in 2007. The serpent of light phenomenon has become one of the most iconic demonstrations of the intersection between ancient astronomy, architecture, and religion.",
