        id: "pueblo-bonito",
        title: "Pueblo Bonito, Chaco Canyon (New Mexico, USA)",
        year: 850,
        yearLabel: "850–1,100 AD",
        description:
          "Pueblo Bonito — 'Beautiful Village' in Spanish — is the largest and most architecturally impressive of the great houses in Chaco Canyon, a remote desert canyon in northwestern New Mexico that was the center of a remarkable pre-Columbian civilization that flourished from approximately 850 to 1,150 AD. At its peak, Pueblo Bonito contained over 600 rooms and 40 kivas (circular ceremonial chambers), making it the largest building in North America until it was surpassed by a New York City apartment building in the 1880s.\n\nPueblo Bonito was not built in a single campaign but grew over a period of approximately 200 to 300 years, with major construction phases occurring in the 10th, 11th, and early 12th centuries. The building is D-shaped in plan, with a massive curved rear wall standing four to five stories tall and a lower row of rooms along the front, enclosing a large central plaza. The construction is of core-and-veneer masonry — thick walls of rubble core faced with carefully coursed sandstone veneer — that is among the finest prehistoric masonry in the Americas.\n\nThe Chacoan people quarried, shaped, and transported approximately 50 million pieces of sandstone for the construction of Pueblo Bonito and the other great houses in the canyon. They also transported an estimated 200,000 wooden beams (primarily spruce and fir logs) from mountain forests 80 to 120 kilometers away, across open desert, without the use of wheels, pack animals, or metal tools. Tree-ring dating (dendrochronology) of these beams has provided remarkably precise construction dates for different parts of the building.\n\nChaco Canyon's significance extends far beyond architecture. The canyon was the center of a vast regional system that encompassed an area of approximately 100,000 square kilometers across the Four Corners region of the American Southwest. Over 150 outlying great houses — smaller but architecturally similar to the canyon buildings — have been identified throughout the region, connected to the canyon by an extensive road system. These roads — averaging 9 meters wide, scraped and smoothed to a level surface, and running in remarkably straight lines across the desert (even ascending and descending cliffs via staircases carved into the rock) — extend for hundreds of kilometers and connect the great houses to the canyon center.\n\nThe astronomical sophistication of the Chacoans is well documented. The rear wall of Pueblo Bonito is aligned precisely along an east-west axis, and the wall that divides the building into two halves runs exactly north-south. The canyon contains several features aligned with solar and lunar events, including the famous 'Sun Dagger' on nearby Fajada Butte — a natural rock formation that produces a sliver of light that bisects a carved spiral on the summer solstice.\n\nThe reasons for Chaco Canyon's abandonment in the mid-12th century remain debated. A severe drought between approximately 1130 and 1180 AD — documented by tree-ring data — is the most commonly cited factor, but evidence of violence, political upheaval, and social stress has also been identified. The descendants of the Chacoans are believed to include the modern Pueblo peoples of the Rio Grande Valley and the Hopi and Zuni of Arizona and western New Mexico.\n\nChaco Canyon was designated a UNESCO World Heritage Site in 1987 and is administered as Chaco Culture National Historical Park by the U.S. National Park Service. Its remote location has helped preserve the site but also makes it one of the more challenging World Heritage Sites to visit.",
